      "writtenOn": "2018-03-22T04:24:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think I now understand the algorithm here. As I\u0027ve pointed out below, it doesn\u0027t handle the case where the new region (area) is very big and overlaps with multiple existing slots. In that case, we can delete/invalidate those existing slots one by one, before adding the new (big) slot. Of course, we\u0027ll have to handle the first and last existing slots with care (in case of a partial overlap).\nIf we make use of slot ids, we can simplify slot management on both QEMU and HAXM (kernel) sides, because we\u0027ll be able to delete/invalidate a slot by its id (invoking SET_RAM2 with size \u003d 0). But even without slot ids, the said algorithm can still be implemented. A big benefit of it is that SET_RAM2 will never be called with a region that overlaps with partial or more than one existing slot, so HAXM no longer needs to split or resize slots.",
      "revId": "a411d8ef278aa9583e096909adeb0c2f66df4e10",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
